## 14. Webhook Integration Design

The webhook route is the operational heart of the Square integration.

## 14.1 Route

`POST /api/square/webhooks`

## 14.2 Route responsibilities

The route must:

- read the raw request body
- determine the notification URL used for signature verification
- read `x-square-hmacsha256-signature`
- verify the webhook signature
- parse the event JSON
- pass the event to the billing processor
- return success or error response

## 14.3 Webhook origin handling

The current implementation resolves the notification URL from:

- `x-forwarded-proto`
- `x-forwarded-host`
- otherwise `request.nextUrl.origin`

This is important because signature validation depends on the exact notification URL.

## 14.4 Security requirement

A webhook must never be processed unless the signature is valid.

---

## 15. Webhook Event Processing Workflow

The billing event processor lives in `src/lib/billing.ts`.

## 15.1 Processing sequence

When a webhook event arrives, the processor currently:

1. extracts the event ID
2. checks `square_webhook_events/{eventId}` for prior processing
3. rejects duplicates
4. extracts the provider event type
5. extracts the subscription payload
6. resolves the Square subscription ID
7. resolves Square customer ID if present
8. normalizes previous and next membership statuses
9. determines payment status if the event is invoice or payment related
10. finds the matching internal plan by `squareSubscriptionPlanVariationId`
11. finds the matching internal user by `squareCustomerId`
12. derives plan code, membership tier, and billing cycle
13. normalizes the lifecycle type
14. calls the lifecycle synchronizer
15. records the event as processed in `square_webhook_events`

## 15.2 Idempotency rule

Event idempotency must be mandatory. Webhook providers retry. That is not a bug. That is a personality trait.

