## 19. Entitlements and Access Control

Square should never directly gate content or services. The platform entitlement model should do that.

## 19.1 Access flow

1. Square event arrives
2. Firestore user and subscription state are updated
3. entitlement logic resolves the effective tier
4. portal features, content, and service access respond accordingly

## 19.2 Current entitlement model

The application already separates:

- membership tier
- billing cycle
- plan code
- content and service access rules

This is the correct design because:

- both monthly and annual Standard resolve to `standard` entitlements
- both monthly and annual Premium resolve to `premium` entitlements
- pricing and lifecycle visibility still remain intact

---

## 20. Promotion and Grant Interaction with Square

The codebase already includes a promotion/access-grant model. This matters because not all elevated access will originate from Square billing.

## 20.1 Promotion architecture present in the app

- `promotions`
- `membership_access_grants`
- grant expiry processing
- lifecycle support for `promotion_granted` and `promotion_expired`

## 20.2 Interaction rule

When effective membership tier is calculated, promotional grants may temporarily elevate a user’s access above their paid subscription tier.

### Example

A user with a paid Standard subscription and an active promotional grant should receive the higher effective tier while the grant is active.

## 20.3 Design implication

The billing system should not assume Square is the only source of access. It is the primary paid source, but not the only one.

